[3] Canada (Ontario)
Date: Thu 30 Mar 2017
Source: Region of Peel [edited]
http://www.peelregion.ca/news/archiveitem.asp?year=2017&month=2&day=30&file=2017230a.xml


Peel Public Health is investigating a confirmed case of measles in a child from Mississauga. Members of the public may have been exposed to measles in a number of settings in Mississauga during the period of 25--27 Mar 2017.

A list of locations and times where people may have been exposed to measles can be found at the URL above. The virus can only live outside the body (e.g., on surfaces and door handles) for up to 2 hours, so people who visited these locations at other times were not exposed.

If people think they were exposed to the virus, they should
- Check their immunization records to make sure they and their children have had 2 doses of the measles vaccine (MMR or MMRV). Their immunization record (yellow card) or doctor can provide this information.
- Two doses of measles vaccine are recommended for anyone born after 1969.
- Watch for symptoms of measles until 21 days after exposure. These include a high fever, cold-like symptoms (cough/runny nose); sore eyes or sensitivity to light; small spots with a white centre on the inside of the mouth; and a red rash lasting 4 -- 7 days.

Peel Public Health is working with the exposure sites to identify and follow up with anyone who visited the locations listed during the times listed and may be at risk. Anyone who shows symptoms should call their health care provider immediately and tell them they have been exposed to measles. DO NOT go to any medical facility without telling them before the appointment that you have been exposed to measles.

Measles is a highly contagious disease that spreads easily through the air. Anyone who has not had 2 doses of a measles vaccine (MMR or MMRV) or who has not had measles in the past is at risk of infection. Infants under 1 year of age, pregnant women and people with weakened immune systems can get very ill with measles.

Peel is also experiencing an increase in mumps activity with 8 cases this year [2017] to date. Ensuring your MMR immunizations are up-to-date is the best way to protect against measles and mumps. Concerned residents should visit http://peelregion.ca/health for news and alerts about measles and mumps.

[Byline: Scott Fry]

